ilage","Forms a complete ring of cartilage","Connects directly to the first tracheal ring","Contains elastic cartilage tissue","Located at the level of the fourth cervical vertebra"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecricoid cartilage forms a complete ring\u003C/strong\u003E of hyaline cartilage in the airway. It is unique among the laryngeal cartilages in forming a complete ring. It is located at the level of the sixth cervical vertebra (C6) and forms an important landmark in the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms a C-shaped ring of cartilage\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the tracheal rings, formed by hyaline cartilage, which are incomplete posteriorly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated at the level of the fourth cervical vertebra\u003C/strong\u003E - The cricoid cartilage is consistently found at C6, not C4\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains elastic cartilage tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - The cricoid cartilage is composed of hyaline cartilage, not elastic cartilage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects directly to the first tracheal ring\u003C/strong\u003E - While close to the first tracheal ring, they are separated by the cricotracheal ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complete ring structure of the cricoid cartilage makes it an important landmark for emergency airway procedures and is a key reference point for cricothyroidotomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cricoid cartilage is the only complete ring of cartilage in the airway.","The cricoid cartilage forms an important anatomical landmark at the level of the sixth cervical vertebra.","The cricoid cartilage is composed o